## Module Breakdown

### Module 1 · Seller Segmentation

![Seller Tiers](charts/module1_seller_tiers.png)

Built a composite scoring model across three dimensions — revenue, 
order volume, and review quality — using `NTILE()` window functions and 
CTEs. Segmented 1,761 qualified sellers into four tiers.
```sql
-- Core logic: quartile scoring across 3 dimensions
NTILE(4) OVER (ORDER BY total_revenue)    AS revenue_q,
NTILE(4) OVER (ORDER BY total_orders)     AS volume_q,
NTILE(4) OVER (ORDER BY avg_review_score) AS quality_q
```

→ Full query: [`sql/module1_seller_segmentation.sql`](sql/module1_seller_segmentation.sql)

---

### Module 2 · Cohort LTV & Retention

![Cohort Retention](charts/module2_cohort_retention.png)

Tracked 18 monthly cohorts (Jan 2017 – Jun 2018) through their 
12-month purchase lifecycle. Used `customer_unique_id` (not 
`customer_id`) to correctly identify returning users across Olist's 
session-based ID system.

Key technical challenge: computed month offsets manually in SQLite 
via string extraction; migrated to DuckDB's `DATEDIFF()` for 
production-grade performance.

→ Full query: [`analysis/module2_cohort.py`](analysis/module2_cohort.py)

---

### Module 3 · Order Conversion Funnel

![Funnel](charts/module3_funnel.png)

Mapped the complete order lifecycle from placement to delivery. 
Calculated stage-level conversion rates and delivery SLA compliance 
using conditional aggregation.

→ Full query: [`analysis/module3_4_analysis.py`](analysis/module3_4_analysis.py)

---

### Module 4 · Revenue Attribution

![Revenue Attribution](charts/module4_revenue_attribution.png)

Decomposed monthly revenue into new vs. returning customer 
contributions using `ROW_NUMBER()` window functions to identify 
each customer's purchase sequence.
```sql
ROW_NUMBER() OVER (
    PARTITION BY customer_unique_id
    ORDER BY MIN(order_purchase_timestamp)
) AS order_rank
```

→ Full query: [`analysis/module3_4_analysis.py`](analysis/module3_4_analysis.py)

